# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: benguet-coffee
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The **AeroPress** is a manual coffeemaker invented by Alan Adler, founder of AeroPress, Inc.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] It consists of a cylindrical brewing chamber, a plunger with an airtight silicone seal, and a screw-on cap which holds a paper or mesh filter.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Coffee is steeped inside, then forced through the filter by pressing the plunger down through the chamber.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The use of pressure makes it capable of brewing highly concentrated coffee, comparable to espresso, but it can also be used to brew filter-strength coffee and cold brew.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The brewer consists of a translucent cylindrical chamber, and a plunger with an airtight silicone seal, similar to a syringe.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] A filter cap is screwed onto the end of the chamber, to hold a small round paper filter in place.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The chamber and plunger are made of translucent plastic.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Early AeroPress models used clear polycarbonate, but in 2009 switched to BPA-free copolyester, then in 2014 to polypropylene.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] According to the company, lab tests found that the original model did not leach BPA into brewed coffee.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The lettering changed color several times and the plastic changed from clear to gray, but the brewer's design was otherwise unchanged between these versions.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In 2023, the company released new clear models made of Tritan.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The base model AeroPress includes a scoop for ground coffee, a stirring paddle, and a pack of paper filters.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Earlier units also included a carrying bag, a plastic holder for the filters, and a funnel for loading coffee and pressing into smaller vessels, but as of 2024 these are sold separately.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] XL models include the scoop, paddle, filters, and a 20oz plastic carafe.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Additional AeroPress accessories, such as pressure-actuated valve caps, reusable metal filters, cold drip adapters, and others, have been available from third-party manufacturers.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Over the years, the company released its own versions of some of these products, including several models of flow-control caps and metal filters.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] AeroPress units ship with a pack of 350 circular paper filters.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In 2017, the manufacturer recommended against using metal mesh filters, claiming that paper filters improved taste.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In contrast, some immersion brewers, such as the French press, are used almost exclusively with metal filters.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] As of 2024, AeroPress sells their own stainless steel mesh filter.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The AeroPress was invented by retired Stanford engineering lecturer Alan Adler, who had previously patented and sold the Aerobie flying ring in the 1980s.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Adler began prototyping the AeroPress in his garage in 2004, with the intention of reducing acidity and bitterness in his daily cup of coffee.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] He expressed dissatisfaction with espresso machines, pour-over, and the French press, and wanted greater control over parameters such as brew time, water temperature, and grind size.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Adler sold the AeroPress through his existing company, Aerobie Inc..
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In 2017, Spin Master purchased the rights to the Aerobie, and the company was renamed to AeroPress, Inc.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In 2019, they released the AeroPress Go, a travel-sized model with a reduced capacity, smaller accessories which assemble inside of a plastic mug with a lid.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In August 2021, Canadian holding company Tiny Capital bought a controlling stake in AeroPress Inc.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The device was officially unveiled in November 2005, at the CoffeeFest trade show in Seattle.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In the years after its release, it gained a cult following among coffee enthusiasts, who praised it for its low cost, flexibility, and consistency in brewing.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The World AeroPress Championship is an international fan-led AeroPress brewing competition.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The event is a multi-round, elimination tournament, in which competitors have five minutes to brew coffee.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] It was first held in Oslo, Norway, in 2008, with only three competitors, but grew in popularity each year after.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The 2018 competition attracted 3,157 competitors from 61 countries.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The 2020 championship was cancelled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The championship resumed in 2021, with both in-person events and a new online format, in which competitors create and submit their recipe remotely.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] According to the instructions, fine-ground coffee is placed in the bottom of the larger cylinder on top of a paper microfilter.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Hot water at approximately 176 °F (80 °C) for dark roast coffee or 185 °F (85 °C) for lighter roast is then poured over the coffee; this mixture is stirred for approximately 10 seconds before being forced through the microfilter by pushing the plunger downwards.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Baristas and coffee drinkers have also developed an inverted brewing technique for the AeroPress.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] In inverted brewing, the plunger is placed into the column from the beginning, close to the "top" of the column, and the entire AeroPress stands upside-down, resting on the top of the plunger.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] One or two scoops of ground coffee are added, followed by water, and the entire mixture then stirred.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] While that brews, a filter is placed into the filter cap and moistened to help it stick in place then the AeroPress cap is placed on top of the column and screwed into place.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Lastly, once the desired brewing time is complete the AeroPress is either turned right-side-up and plunged normally or held at an angle and plunged horizontally.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] This method is more similar to the French press, particularly the extended brewing time in which the grounds and water sit together.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] This makes it useful for using grinds that wouldn't be optimal in the official method such as coarse grinds that might be used in a French press.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] The AeroPress may use a finer grind than other immersion brewers and may take less time to brew coffee, sometimes around 30 seconds.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] Pressure is used by the AeroPress to aid in extraction, unlike the French press, the siphon brew, or most other immersion coffee brewers.
[src:benguet-coffee/aeropress] According to AeroPress, it produces coffee with one-fifth the acidity of drip coffee and one-ninth that of French press.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] Cafés usually serve the affogato in a tall glass with a narrow bottom, allowing the gelato to melt and combine with the espresso at the bottom of the glass.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] Occasionally, coconut, berries, honeycomb, and multiple flavors of gelato are added.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] In Italy the affogato is often categorized as a dessert, while outside of Italy restaurants and cafés categorize it as a beverage.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] Affogatos are often drunk as a post-meal coffee-dessert combo eaten with a spoon or drunk with a straw.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] While the recipe of the affogato is more or less standard in Italy, consisting of a scoop of *fiordilatte* (plain milk-flavored) or vanilla gelato topped with a shot of espresso, variations exist in European and North American restaurants.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] Various desserts of gelato in other liquids are documented, including whisky, hot chocolate, kirsch, vin santo, and port wine.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] The origins of the affogato are unknown.
[src:benguet-coffee/affogato] English-language dictionaries document the use of *affogato* in 1988.
[src:benguet-coffee/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:benguet-coffee/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:benguet-coffee/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:benguet-coffee/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:benguet-coffee/alaminos-longganisa] It is made with ground lean pork, ground pork fat, brown sugar, coarse salt, saltpeter, black pepper, bay leaf, vinegar, and garlic in hog casings.
[src:benguet-coffee/alaminos-longganisa] It is slightly sour, garlicky taste, typically bright yellow or orange due to the use of *achuete* seeds, made in bite-sized pieces.
[src:benguet-coffee/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is named after the Spanish “longaniza,” and is sometimes used interchangeably with the chorizo.
[src:benguet-coffee/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is a type of local sausage with two major types—the recado, with a more savory flavor, and the hamonado, with a sweet taste.
[src:benguet-coffee/alaminos-longganisa] Unlike other longganisa variants, the Alaminos longganisa's segments of the sausage are uniquely divided by small pieces of coconut leaf midribs (sometimes mistaken for toothpicks), making it easily identifiable.
[src:benguet-coffee/alaminos-longganisa] Each sausage string usually has six segments and is traditionally tied at the end with a length of buli palm fiber.
[src:benguet-coffee/alaminos-longganisa] The sausages are celebrated in an annual "Longganisa Festival" in Alaminos.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] An ***alfajor*** or ***alajú*** (Spanish pronunciation: [alfaˈxoɾ], plural *alfajores*) is a traditional confection.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Originally from present-day Spain, it is found now in Argentina, Bolivia, Southern Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, El Salvador, Southern France, Paraguay, Peru, the Philippines, Uruguay, and Venezuela.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The alfajor was born in Iberia during the rule of al-Andalus.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The Spanish alfajor is produced in the form of a small cylinder and is sold either individually or in boxes containing several pieces.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Traditional alfajores in Argentina, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn flour joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] More modern "industrial" varieties in Uruguay and Argentina, are coated with dark or white chocolate (many *alfajores* are sold in "black" and "white" versions), or simply covered with powdered sugar.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The word had been introduced into Spanish dictionaries in the 14th century.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] A similar sweet called *alaú* is found in the Arabic-Hispanic cookbook Kitab al-Tabikh, by an anonymous author.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The Spanish grammarian Nebrija noted the word for the first time in his Latin-Spanish Dictionary (1495) as: *alfaxor* or *alaxur*.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In the 12th century, Raimundo Martin describes in his book *Vocabulista* another possible etymology of the Hispano-Arabic *fasur*, meaning "nectar".
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The publication of historical dictionaries of the Spanish language allows one to document both forms of the original *alajur*, written as *alajú* and *alfajor*.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] *Alajur* and multiple geographic variations are sweets made of a paste of almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs and honey.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In the Americas, the word *alfajor* was not known until the 19th century.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In Spain, there are a variety of different recipes for preparing *alfajores*, but the most traditional contain flour, honey, almonds and several spices, such as cinnamon.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] *Alfajores* are most commonly sold around Christmas.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The traditional Spanish *alfajor* has been produced in Medina-Sidonia (where it is called an *alajú*) since ancient times, and the recipe has been traditionally handed down from father to son.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In this town, there is an account of Mariano Pardo de Figueroa, writing under the pen name Dr.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Thebussem, wherein he wrote that on 2 July 1487, Enrique de Guzmán, second count of Medina Sidonia, ordered the council and majors of the region to send to Malaga 50 cows, 50 oxen, 200 calves and provision of *alajú* from his city.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] On 15 September 2004, protected geographical indication was ratified by the *Consejo de agricultura y pesca de la junta de Andalucía* and published in the *Official Journal of the European Union* as *Alfajor de Medina Sidonia* on 6 March 2007.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The regulations of the Andalusian Ministry of Agriculture allow the use of only pure honey, almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs, sugar, flour and spices, such as aniseed, sesame, cilantro, cloves and cinnamon.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] These *alfajores* are meant to be presented in a cylindrical shape, with a minimum weight of 30 grams (1.1 oz) each, and with a minimum size of about 7 centimetres (2.8 in) in length and a diameter of 1.5 centimetres (0.59 in).
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Each of them will be protected with a wrapping paper, and the ends made an ornament in a spiral shape with a ribbon out of the same paper.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Once individually wrapped, they may be packaged in wood or cardboard boxes, but never in plastic.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In the province of Cuenca, Spain, where the *alfajor* is called *alajú,* it is made with almond, honey and figs, wrapped in a wafer.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In Puerto Rico, they underwent creolization, lost their almond and gained ground cassava.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] They can take varying amounts of sugar and spices.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] It is possible that Puerto Rico's most common version of this dessert (the South American version with dulce de leche) reached Puerto Rico from Venezuela, but the opposite is also possible.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Depending on region some add cornstarch, citrus zest, ginger and honey, filled with chocolate, vanilla cream, dulce de leche, fruit paste, or coconut.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The filling can be mixed with almonds, sesame seeds, coconut flakes, or sprinkles.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Traditional "alfajores" in Chile, Argentina,and Uruguay consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn starch joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] These are also known as a *Chilean Oreo*.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] One variation is called "*alfajor de nieve*" (snow alfajor) and has a white coating consisting of a mixture of egg whites and sugar.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Most *alfajores* come packaged in aluminium foil.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Alfajores are made in various diameters and are consumed as snacks.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The *alfajor* has been manufactured and consumed since colonial times in the territories that today belong to Argentina.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The filling is usually dulce de leche, although there are many variations.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] They can be covered with powder sugar (the traditional ones), glazed sugar (Santafesinos or "de nieve"), grated coconut or chocolate.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Argentina is one of the world's largest consumers of alfajores, both in total numbers and in per capita calculations, consuming more than a billion alfajores a year.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] One important Argentine alfajor is the alfajor de Santa Fe or the alfajor santafesino, which has three puff pastry layers adhered to one another with dulce de leche and glazed all over.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] This alfajor is closely linked to the history of the city of Santa Fe.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Colonel Néstor Fernández from Santa Fe took it to the Battle of Caseros in 1851.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] It became so popular with the army that General Justo José de Urquiza had a weekly shipment of these alfajores delivered to his estancia in San José de Entre Ríos.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The production of Santa Fe alfajores began in 1851 in a shop located on the southwest corner of San Jerónimo and 3 de Febrero streets, a few meters from the Cabildo (where the Santa Fe Government House currently stands).
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] These alfajores became known throughout the country after the 24 writers of the constitution, who, after living in Santa Fe for six months, took this dessert home as a souvenir.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Today, it is a heritage of the city of Santa Fe and is handcrafted in that city and its surrounding areas.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The nickname "Merengo" gave rise to a brand of alfajores.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The Cordobes alfajor is filled with fruit jellies (generally of quince).
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In addition, there is the Rogel, similar to the Santa Fe but bigger (the size of a small cake) and a variety from Tucuman known as a clarita, with two crunchy cookies and filled with a jelly made up of sugar molasses.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] In Argentina, alfajores made up of cornflour are very consumed as well (covers made up of maize starch, filled with dulce de leche and grated coconut around the filling).
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Mass-production of alfajores traces back to the Atlantic coast of Argentina in the 1950s.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Brands such as Havanna and Balcarce, and as many as 30 others, have been introduced into shops and supermarkets.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Statistics of the year 2021 shows that inhabitants of Argentina consume 6 million alfajores per day.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Two types of alfajores are found in Chile.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The first type of alfajor, similar to the one of corn flour prepared in other countries of Latin America, is prepared over all the territory of Chile, but mainly in the central area of Chile.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] It is known as "candy of corn flour" or, more typically, "chilenitos".
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The chilenitos are manufactured with corn flour or other types of flour and tend to be simpler and smaller than the other alfajores.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The second type of alfajor, considered the true traditional alfajor of the country and known as "chilean alfajor", is mainly prepared in the southern areas of Chile, generally for the patriotic festivities of September.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] It is prepared with two hojarascas (a thin and firm cookie) that, since they are previously baked, acquire a curved form.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] They are adhered to each other with dark brown sugar, panela, manjar or with confectioners cream.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Optionally, they can be garnished in the end of the filling with grated coconut as it is the case of the alfajores filled with manjar or with ground nuts.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Alfajores made their arrival to the Viceroyalty of Peru, the largest administrative district of the Spanish Empire in South America in the 16th century, and have been popular since, especially the artisanal types.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Alfajor de Trujillo is a type of alfajor from Trujillo.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The *alfajor de Trujillo* has several layers and it can be of different sizes and shapes as round or square.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] It is made mainly with products as flour, butter, eggs and milk, filled with milk candy, some pineapple sweet and in some cases peanuts, with cookies within its layers.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The most famous company manufacturing this products in Trujillo is Dulcería Castañeda, which has locations in Trujillo and Lima and has been making them since 1925.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The mass of the alfajor is made of flour, eggs, margarine, salt, and water.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The filling is made with figs, quince, walnuts, blancmange.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] It is one of the products presented in the Gastronomic Fair in Trujillo.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] Another variant of the alfajor de trujillo is King Kong milk candy, which is made in both Trujillo and Lambayeque.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] According to Guinness World Records, the biggest *alfajor* in the world, measuring almost 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in diameter and 80 centimetres (31 in) in height and weighing 464 kilograms (1,023 lb), was made on 11 December 2010 in Minas, Lavalleja Department, Uruguay.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] The giant *alfajor* was made to mark the celebration of Uruguay's first National Alfajor Festival.
[src:benguet-coffee/alfajor] More than 30 people participated in the preparation of the record-breaking *alfajor*.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Arabica coffee is believed to have been introduced to the Cordillera highlands in the mid-19th century.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Pack, an American governor of Benguet (1909–1912) during the American colonial period, arabica coffee was first introduced to the Cordilleras in 1875 by a Spanish military governor of Benguet, Manuel Scheidnegal y Sera.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] He initially planted them in government gardens in the lowlands of the province to evaluate their potential as a regional crop.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] However, frequent rains and the low altitude were not ideal conditions for the plants.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] The next governor, Enrique Oraa, had greater success when he transplanted them at higher altitudes in 1877 and distributed seedlings among the native Igorot people.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] In 1881 however, the then governor, a certain Villena, attempted to coerce the natives into growing coffee by ordering them to do so.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] In protest, native communities destroyed arabica plantations at the advice of village elders.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] However, a native chief named Camising from Kabayan purportedly saw the benefits of the crop and introduced arabica coffee to his own people.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] His successes convinced neighboring communities to take up coffee cultivation on their own.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Benguet coffee was part of the booming coffee industry of the Philippines during the 1880s and 1890s, which reached annual coffee exports of up to 16 million pounds.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] However, coffee rust devastated the plantations in 1899 and coffee production plummeted.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] By 1917, annual total export of coffee from the Philippines only amounted to around 3,000 pounds.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Pack praised Benguet coffee even then for its flavor and spearheaded a plan to rehabilite the industry while he was governor.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] However, his efforts and that of the American colonial government failed.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Benguet coffee cultivation is centered in the province of Benguet, mostly in backyard or small-scale farms.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] The coffee they produced were both for local consumption and sold as luxury exports to Spain, where they fetched high prices.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] The coffee industry flourished in the mid-20th century as demand increased.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] But it faltered in the 1990s due to rapidly rising inflation and government neglect, resulting in farmers shifting to other crops like corn.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] In recent years, provincial governments are attempting to bring back coffee production for both local and international markets.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Production has steadily increased since 2010.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] In 2016, the Department of Trade and Industry in Cordillera launched a shared service facility and laboratory for processing and cupping arabica in the Benguet State University, the first in the country.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Benguet is regarded as the top producer of quality arabica coffee in the Philippines and is in high demand.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] The Philippine coffee roadmap, which is the blue print of the country's coffee industry, aims to put the Philippines' coffee sufficiency level at 161% by the year 2022.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] To be able to reach this goal, production volume has to increase by 145, 969.79 metric tons, production area has to expand by 99,879 hectares, and productivity will have to increase by 0.50 MT to make it 1 MT per hectare.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] In the Cordillera region coffee production is pegged to be at 3,735.86 MT of green beans coming from 6,322 hectares production area.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Benguet coffee is characterized as having an acidity comparable to Hawaiian Kona coffee and Jamaican Blue Mountain coffee.
[src:benguet-coffee/benguet-coffee] Benguet coffee is listed in the Ark of Taste international catalogue of endangered heritage foods by the Slow Food movement.
